Review in 3 phases:

Phase 1 — Test Adequacy:
- Do tests verify behavior that would fail under wrong implementation?
- Are plan-declared boundary conditions covered?
- Are tests not just tautological mirrors of implementation?

Phase 2 — Behavioral Correctness:
A. Correctness: implementation matches intent, edge cases, exception paths
B. Boundary conditions: empty/single/overflow inputs for each new function
C. Integration: imports complete, callers updated, API compatible
D. Security: no hardcoded keys, input validation, no injection vectors
E. Architecture: import direction correct, no cross-module internal access, files <300 lines, single responsibility
G. Regression: does modification affect unplanned features?

Phase 3 — Non-tested Risks:
- Untested side effects: state, concurrency, permissions, idempotency, null values
- Is implementation overfitted to pass tests?

Finding Classification: code-bug / test-gap / design-concern / suggestion
PASS/FAIL: code-bug or test-gap HIGH/MED unfixed → FAIL

